project1.description: Captcha This generates a random grid of images (similar to an image captcha) corresponding to a search term entered by a user. A user is given the opportunity to solve the captcha by selecting the correct images that correspond to their search term. Captcha This is deployed on the Google App Engine and uses the Bing Image Search API for gathering image URLs. Sixteen top trending images are gathered from the Bing API that correspond to the provided search term. As this web application is meant to mimic an image captcha, not all images used in the grid are related to the user's search term. These unrelated images are gathered via Bing API requests from previous search terms entered by users as well as some hard-coded search terms. Moreover, previous used image URLs are cached, which effectively decreases the amount of requests made to the Bing API.
project1.goals: In future iterations, I intend to improve the UI's design and responsiveness. I also want to explore ways of reworking the app for practical use similar to that of a functional captcha system.

project2.description: Promptu is a prompt-based anonymous message board that features anonymous user authentication, random AI-generated discussion prompts, comment sections, comment upvote/downvote functionality, and comment awarded badges. It runs on web and Android. The purpose of this app is to serve as an anonymous discussion board, for which reason users authenticate anonymously with no credentials, user display names are randomly generated, and user features are generally limited (no user interfaces, etc). Local storage on a browser or mobile device is used to persist user state across multiple sessions and is not retrievable once cleared. The app's 10 daily discussion prompts reset daily and are replaced with new AI-generated discussed prompts. At reset, the app makes a request to one of my microservices that retrieves AI-generated discussion prompts from the OpenAI Text Completions API. With each reset, all user comments in previous discussion sections are deleted from the app's Firestore database.
project2.goals: Next, I plan to add a comment filter feature to the prompt topic screens, and make some general UI improvments.

project3.description: Mini Shell is a C programmed shell that is built and tested to run on top of the Bash Unix Shell. The shell interprets Unix commands as well as features some built-in commands and basic variable expansion. The shell supports input/output redirection and background process designation. The primary purpose of this project was for gaining exposure to lower level programming where I worked with forking and monitoring system processes and using signal handlers. The end product was a fully functional shell that I run on top of bash.
project3.goals: The program is a self-contained command line oriented program. I've done thorough manual testing and automated testing using shell scripts, so at this point the only improvement I would make is to the code itself. Currently, the program is a one file program which feels tentative, so I aim to modularize it with a sensible file structure.

project4.description: Shipping Port is a REST API that allows users to interact with and manipulate two related data entities: boats and loads. The API is meant to be used to simulate a system for tracking cargo ships and their cargo. Interaction with the API occurs via HTTP requests made to the app's various endpoints. An authenticated user with a valid JSON Web Token (JWT) can freely create their own boat and load data entities, and perform data entity interactions (like loading or unloading loads from a boat). The API has had thorough automated and manual testing, has full specification documentation, and follows the standards of RESTful design.
project4.goals: Currently, the authentication web page that redirects users to Auth0 (performs authentication and generates JWTs) has a fairly barebones UI. While this is not my highest priority, it could definitely use a fresh coat of paint. I also want to introduce some new attributes to the boat entity that will allow it to better simulate how real cargo ships are identified. I also foresee improvements to the naming conventions for my APIs data entities and their respective attributes.

project5.stack: ReactJS, NodeJS, HTML CSS, PostgreSQL, Firebase
project5.description: My Journal is a blogging web application. The application features email/password authentication and essential CRUD operations that allow users to create, view, edit, and delete their own blog posts. Users can choose to either make their posts public or private. The latest public posts from all users are displayed on the application's home page. All user and user post data is stored on a database managed with PostgreSQL. The blog uses a minimalist grayscale UI design.
project5.goals: The first iteration of My Journal is near complete in my development environment. My next step will be to get the application and its database deployed and hosted online. I intend to use Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL and either Firebase or Google Cloud Platform for hosting the application.
